// Microbenchmark for Map<str, int> set/get/keys.
//
// This is the P6 baseline reference: we measure today's
// C-emitted `_map_set` / `_map_get` / `_map_keys` performance
// before rewriting std/map in pure Potato. After the rewrite,
// the same workload running through `Map<str, int>` (the
// monomorphised user-defined type) must come within 1.2× of
// the timing captured here.
//
// The harness is intentionally simple: each phase performs N
// operations and prints a sentinel so the test runner can
// confirm the work happened. Wall-clock measurement happens
// via `time` outside the .ptt file (no built-in timing yet).
//
// Phases:
//   1. set: insert N distinct keys.
//   2. get: read every key back (forces every bucket walk).
//   3. keys: enumerate the map and sum the values.
//
// N=512 is small enough for the test suite (sub-second at
// any -O level today) but large enough that the loop dominates
// any fixed setup cost.

spark {
  m is map of str to int

  // Phase 1: set 512 distinct keys.
  through (i from 0 to 512 by 1) {
    k is "k{i}"
    m.set(k, i * 7)
  }
  yell(len(m))                          // 512 — confirms inserts done

  // Phase 2: read every key back; sum the values to keep the
  // compiler from dead-code-eliminating the loads.
  total is 0
  through (i from 0 to 512 by 1) {
    k is "k{i}"
    total be total + m.get(k)
  }
  yell(total)                           // sum_{i=0..511} i*7 = 7 * (511*512/2) = 915712

  // Phase 3: enumerate keys and sum values via lookup.
  ks is m.keys()
  ksum is 0
  through (k in ks) {
    ksum be ksum + m.get(k)
  }
  yell(ksum)                            // same as total: 915712
}
